    <stitle>Electrical System Troubleshooting Guide - BE 200, CE 200, CE 300 Model - ELECTRICAL SYSTEM CONTROLLER AND
        SWITCH PACKS - Left Hand Switch Panel - Function
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="x08290018ggg" svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="1">
        <title>Function</title>
        <figure id="f08290423" figsize="pg-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg08/G08290420.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                     scalefitheight="392px"/>
            <caption>Left Hand Switch Panel Function Diagram</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. POWER SOURCE</callout1>
                <callout1>2. LEFT HAND SWITCH PANEL</callout1>
                <callout1>3. DESIGNATED SWITCH FUNCTION</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <para>The
            <hotlnk xrefid="f08290423">left hand switch panel</hotlnk>
            contains switches that control several different systems and features on the BE/CE Bus. The switches connect
            a power supply or ground to a specific function depending on the features installed on the BE/CE Bus. The
            left hand switch panel has no connection to the ESC therefore new functions can be added to the BE/CE Bus
            without having to reprogram the ESC.
        </para>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>When adding a new function to the BE or CE Bus, IC Corporation should be contacted to determine if
                    the feature needs to be installed in the switch pack connected to the ESC or if it can be installed
                    in the left hand switch panel.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <para>The mechanical assembly for each switch snaps into the switch receptacle and can be released from the rear
            of the switch panel. Different mechanical assemblies determine the actuation of the switch. Blank covers are
            used when a switch receptacle is not being used.
        </para>
        <para>The function of each switch location is dependant on the system or feature that is wired to the switch
